The Great Leader's Revival
The Battle of Waterloo in London has been over for two hundred years, and Napoleon's disastrous defeat in that battle severely damaged France's pride, to the extent that General Charles de Gaulle did not mention it at all when writing the history of the French army.
Despite this, if you acknowledge that "great" is a personal trait of some sort, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be called the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader" in the first place.
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created an environment in which such an "odd and incompetent" person like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not a particularly outstanding general; his victories should be attributed to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon was great or not, we need to clarify whether it's possible to describe any leader as great.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important standards.
First, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck achieved that, as did his fellow German Konrad Adenauer; quoting Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard the "sound of the Lord's coat rustling."
Secondly, did this leader make important decisions?
Certainly, if a leader is forced to make a decision, he or she cannot be blamed for it, nor can he or she take credit for it.
Therefore, the key lies in whether the leader has the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the correct decision on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle should therefore be renowned in any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-war doldrums.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, suppressed two attempted coups, ended the Algerian War, and drafted the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their place in the post-war global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in shaping their respective national worldviews was somewhat exaggerated.
Their successors would later view the world – and their country's role in it – in a way that was constrained by rationality and distorted decision-making, for years to come.
As a result, the leaders of the two countries that followed were unable to achieve accomplishments comparable to those of the two great leaders.
However, there was another British prime minister who could be compared to them: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure, with as many people liking her as disliking her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was a result of the internal rebellion within her cabinet and party.
It is not necessary to win the hearts of everyone to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her impact.
Except for being the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, she was also the first female Prime Minister of almost every other country in the world, and Thatcher helped to turn around Britain's economic decline.
Not only that, but her attack on the overly powerful unions made the country more manageable at a time when it seemed to be sliding into chaos and disorder.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be a candidate for "great leader".
Similarly, although far from flawless, China's Deng Xiaoping also has the qualifications to be a great leader.
Aside from assisting Mao Zedong in his evil deeds, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng simultaneously revitalized the market, leading China onto an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted millions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people consider Singapore's founding leader and long-time Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew to be extremely great, even though he might have wanted to make a greater impact on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect whether someone can become a great leader.
I mean no disrespect when I say that small countries like Luxembourg are unlikely to produce great leaders, especially given the country's relatively uncontroversial political climate.
The United States, with its vast territory, can certainly serve as a place where great leaders are born.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a lot.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower – although not intellectual giants – demonstrated exceptional judgment in establishing the post-war international order that has supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possess a high natural talent – the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was a man of many talents.
He accomplished a great task: resolving the Cuban Missile Crisis.
He had unmatched charisma; in fact, his assassination after his death only solidified the traditions he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has been called a great figure since the death of President Mandela, who embodied courage, authority, and elegant magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most captivating and charming leader I have ever met; the other two - former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell - are either not African or of African American descent.
So, what about today?
The only one who can rightfully call themselves great is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at first but rarely made mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl drafted the generous terms for German unification; Merkel stood up to Putin when he invaded Ukraine and took a tolerant approach to the migrant crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders – the exercisers of political power – can change the course of events, whether for the better or for the worse.
Merkel is a clear example today, pointing the way for Europe to navigate its high-stakes survival crisis.
